{
  "enabled": true,
  "name": "2 · EOD: Meeting Sync",
  "description": "Multi-source meeting ingestion: Hedy + Amazon Meeting Summary + email threads → meetings/ series files + organ updates. Run after meetings.",
  "version": "2",
  "when": {
    "type": "userTriggered"
  },
  "then": {
    "type": "askAgent",
    "prompt": "Run the Hedy meeting sync. The Hedy MCP tools are already available (GetSessions, GetSessionDetails, GetSessionHighlights, GetSessionToDos, ListSessionContexts, GetAllTopics, UpdateSessionContext, UpdateTopic).\n\nSPEED RULES (non-negotiable):\n- Do ALL reads before ANY writes.\n- Never interleave analysis with file edits. Finish thinking, then write.\n- Write to meetings/ series files FIRST. They're the single source of truth. Organ updates come after.\n- For Hedy topic audit, ONLY check topics that had a session today. Skip dormant topics entirely.\n- When updating organs, make ONE strReplace per organ file if possible (replace the whole section, not individual lines).\n- If a session has no cleaned_transcript and the raw transcript is mostly garbled (R&O tags, no speaker labels), note it as 'low-quality transcript' and score what you can from the meeting_minutes and recap instead.\n\nMEETING NOTES SYSTEM:\nMeeting context lives in ~/shared/context/meetings/ — one file per meeting series.\nRead ~/shared/context/meetings/README.md for the full ingestion protocol, source priority, and cleaning rules.\nThe README contains the Multi-Source Ingestion Protocol (Hedy → Amazon Meeting Summary → Email threads → Synthesize ONE summary) and Cleaning During Ingestion rules. Follow them.\n\nSTEP 1 — PULL (all reads, no writes):\n1a. GetSessions with limit=10. Filter to sessions from today (check startTime date). If Richard says a specific date range, use that instead.\n1b. For each session from today, call GetSessionDetails and GetSessionToDos. Do these in parallel where possible.\n1c. Check Outlook Auto-meeting folder for Amazon Meeting Summaries matching today's meetings.\n1d. Check Outlook inbox for email threads related to today's meetings (±2 days).\n1e. Read these ground truth files: ~/shared/context/active/current.md, ~/shared/context/body/nervous-system.md (Loop 7 section and Loop 3 pattern tracking only).\n1f. Read the relevant meetings/ series files for each session (use the Hedy Topic ID → Series File Map in README.md).\n\nSTEP 2 — ANALYZE (no tool calls, just thinking):\nFor each session, assess:\n- Meeting type: 1:1 or group? Who was there?\n- Speaking share: From transcript or cleaned_transcript, estimate Richard's share. In group meetings, flag if below 15%.\n- Hedging: Note instances of 'I think', 'probably', 'sort of', 'I guess', 'my intuition is'. Note where Richard was direct.\n- Strategic contributions: Count moments where Richard framed a problem, proposed a direction, connected cross-market dots, or challenged an assumption.\n- Comfort zone pushes: Did Richard do something he normally avoids?\n- Closed loops: Did Richard end with clear commitments (who/what/when)?\n- Action items: What did Richard commit to? What's due when?\n- Relationship updates: Any new info about attendees that should update memory.md relationship graph?\n- Stakeholder changes: Anyone new, departed, or changed role?\n- Apply the Cleaning During Ingestion rules from meetings/README.md — strip Hedy artifacts, cross-check stale action items, deduplicate, etc.\n\nSTEP 3 — UPDATE MEETINGS/ SERIES FILES (primary output):\nFor each session, update the corresponding series file in ~/shared/context/meetings/:\n- Follow the Multi-Source Ingestion Protocol from README.md\n- Synthesize ONE clean 'Latest Session' entry from all sources (Hedy + Amazon Meeting Summary + email threads)\n- Move previous 'Latest Session' to 'Previous Sessions' if needed\n- Update 'Open Items' — close completed, add new\n- Update 'Running Themes' if patterns shifted\n- Update 'Outlook Context' section if email threads added new pre/post-meeting context\n- If a meeting doesn't have a series file yet, create one following the file format in README.md\n\nSTEP 4 — UPDATE ORGANS (secondary — only what meetings/ doesn't cover):\nOrgans should NOT duplicate meeting content. They get only what's specific to their function:\n4a. memory.md — Update relationship graph entries ONLY (tone, draft style, last interaction date). Do NOT update meeting prep briefs (those live in meetings/ now). Update compressed context if roles changed.\n4b. nervous-system.md — Update Loop 7 scorecard (weekly row) and per-stakeholder trajectory table. Update Loop 3 pattern tracking if group silence or hedging patterns changed. This is calibration data, not meeting content.\n4c. current.md — Update key people table if anyone changed roles. Update pending actions if new commitments were made. Do NOT duplicate meeting summaries here.\n4d. device.md — Update delegation protocols only if a delegation target changed (e.g., someone left).\n\nSTEP 5 — AUDIT HEDY CONTEXTS:\n5a. ListSessionContexts. Compare the default session context against current.md for factual accuracy (team, projects, people, markets). If stale, UpdateSessionContext.\n5b. GetAllTopics. For each topic that had a session today: check its topicContext against the corresponding meetings/ series file. If attendees, projects, or dynamics are wrong, UpdateTopic. For topics with NO session today: skip entirely unless Richard asks.\n5c. For topics with null topicContext that had a session today: create a context based on the session data.\n\nSTEP 6 — REPORT:\nTell Richard:\n- How many sessions processed\n- Which meetings/ series files were updated\n- Key communication flags (speaking share violations, hedging patterns)\n- Key relationship changes\n- What organs were updated (and what specifically — not 'updated memory.md' but 'updated Lorena relationship entry in memory.md')\n- What Hedy contexts were updated vs skipped\n- Action items that should go into tomorrow's morning routine"
  }
}